narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: Fundamental algebraic principles, introductory calculus, and problem solving skills

I learned a lot this fall in math 110. I was able to further development  my understanding of derivatives and limits which I started in high school. Overall I took a lot of information away from this course that I hope to bring with me in the future and in math 111.
I learned skills for calculus that can be used in my other courses.

I developed an intuition about instantaneous rates of change and how functions relate to its graphs. I think it was very helpful that the curse emphasized understanding mathematical concepts from scratch and not accepting formulas without any understanding.
I learned a Pre-calculus level of math.
Time management: having a set routine of explorations, psets, and concept checks made it necessary to plan out when you would attend  office hours and complete the work
It helped me brush up on my basic calculus skills.
Learned calculus
How to effectively communicate and solve intro to calculus problems

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: Very engaging professor, reliable problem set/ concept check structure
I feel like the engagement in this course was great however I feel that more breakdown of each individual topic would help more than just going through the practice problems.

Strengths: learned material, a lot of support from ulas 

Weakness: teaching format using canvas videos

The course is very organized, the ULAs are great and there are a lot of office hours. I also always received feedback and it was very clear.  However, I would have liked if the instructor answered my questions when I communicated with him via email.

The strengths included the accessibility of office hours and the encouraged partner work during class. The biggest weakness were the mandatory workshops. Many of these didn't help further my understanding in the course and felt like a waste of time.

Strength: material was well-explained, and I felt constantly supported by TF's.
Weakness: More in-class work could be done (like completing worksheet problems)

Strengths: clear structure and organization. Super good teaching infrastructure: accessible office hours, helpful ULA's, good supplementary videos on canvas.
Weakness: Not everybody should have to go to workshops.
assignments should be graded sooner
Very hard, teacher moves very fast and doesnt explain well

Strengths of this course involve its engaging and guided class time. There was time dedicated to learning new material while also allowing students to break off into groups to solve practice problems, making the classroom more collaborative which fit well with different learning needs. Psets were typically more challenging than what was worked in class which would often lead to full office hours.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Yes
Yes I would because it helped me garner an understanding of mathematics that will help with my future and potentially in other classes I want to take while at Yale.
Yes. Good for STEM majors

Yes. I think having a solid intuition on math and calculus is essential to almost any career in general. I think that through this course I was able to build that base that will help me in other areas I want to pursue/
Yes, especially if you did not understand calculus the first time in high school or wish to understand it more thoroughly.
Yes. If you want to review basic calculus skills, then take this class.
As someone who did not take calculus in high school, I would recommend this course to those who have a shaky precalc background. If you are confident, consider 112.
yes because it a basic calculus class and gives u a strong foundation for any major
No, very hard for what it is
I would recommend this course to anyone who is not as comfortable with math but is looking to improve especially if their major is STEM focused.
